			<p class="comment-author">
				<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/499bebc819a5deb0524049d75b77f286?s=48&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/499bebc819a5deb0524049d75b77f286?s=96&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' loading='lazy'/><span itemprop="name"><a href="http://www.gowp.com" class="comment-author-link" rel="external nofollow" itemprop="url">Lucas Karpiuk</a></span> 			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2014-09-03T17:34:00-07:00" itemprop="datePublished"><a href="https://blog.sucuri.net/2014/09/slider-revolution-plugin-critical-vulnerability-being-exploited.html#comment-6039">September 3, 2014</a></time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>Sucuri to the rescue yet again, thanks!</p>
<p>This appears to have been patched in version 4.2: <a href="http://codecanyon.net/item/slider-revolution-responsive-wordpress-plugin/2751380#item-description__version-4-2-skywood-25th-february-2014-including-security-fix" rel="nofollow ugc">http://codecanyon.net/item/slider-revolution-responsive-wordpress-plugin/2751380#item-description__version-4-2-skywood-25th-february-2014-including-security-fix</a></p>
<p>We thankfully only found one site of the ~250 we maintain that was affected and were able to apply a manual patch to the UniteImageViewRev::outputImage() function in revslider/inc_php/framework/image_view.class.php</p>
<p>I&#8217;m not a security expert, but adding a simple check of the file extension there seems to be working for us.</p>
		</div>

		
		
	</article>
