	<li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-4024">
	<article >

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/ba077bebc759ad92017de9e764b8cfd7?s=48&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/ba077bebc759ad92017de9e764b8cfd7?s=96&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' loading='lazy'/><span itemprop="name"><a href="http://caseyis.me" class="comment-author-link" rel="external nofollow" itemprop="url">Casey Fulgenzi</a></span> 			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2014-09-05T20:51:00-07:00" itemprop="datePublished"><a href="https://blog.sucuri.net/2014/09/slider-revolution-plugin-critical-vulnerability-being-exploited.html#comment-4024">September 5, 2014</a></time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>@blueprintmarketing:disqus  I talked with Flywheel and they actually said it wouldn&#8217;t do anyone any good getting a wp-config file from one of their sites.</p>
<p>&#8220;Due to the way we structure our servers and databases on Flywheel, there is little to nothing that someone could possibly do with access to the wp-config file. Since we dont have a forward facing database manager aside from the one inside your Flywheel account, its pretty much a dead end&#8230;.Theres no way to connect to the database externally, so having that information (password in config) doesnt do them any good.&#8221;</p>
<p>Another benefit of managed WP Hosting!</p>
<p>CC: @perezbox:disqus</p>
