	<li class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-4048">
	<article >

		
		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author">
				<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/c30605d8662cb877f8fed94224f2bb23?s=48&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/c30605d8662cb877f8fed94224f2bb23?s=96&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' loading='lazy'/><span itemprop="name"><a href="http://www.larismedia.com" class="comment-author-link" rel="external nofollow" itemprop="url">Troy Glancy</a></span> 			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2014-09-09T18:08:00-07:00" itemprop="datePublished"><a href="https://blog.sucuri.net/2014/09/slider-revolution-plugin-critical-vulnerability-being-exploited.html#comment-4048">September 9, 2014</a></time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>If you&#8217;re hosting your own server with modsec you can use this rule to block it until your clients sites are patched. </p>
<p>SecRule ARGS_GET &#8220;wp-config.php&#8221; &#8220;t:lowercase,deny,status:403,log,id:9876543,msg:&#8217;wp-config query string'&#8221;</p>
		</div>

		
		
